<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="107" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="107">Distribution and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="107">Tonle Sap River in Kampong Chhnang Province and Tonle Sap Lake at Kampong Chhnang and Siem Reap Provinces, Sen River in Kampong Thom Province, Sangkae River, Battambang Province (locality no. 8, 11, 16, 23, 27, 36, 37, 38 and 40); in soft muddy substrate.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="107" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="107">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="107">
Not sold for food, collected as by-catch of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ng &amp; Jeratthitikul &amp; Sutcharit &amp; Chhuoy &amp; Pin &amp; Pholyotha &amp; Siriwut &amp; Srisonchai &amp; Hogan &amp; Ngor" authorityYear="2020" class="Bivalvia" family="Cyrenidae" genus="Corbicula" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Corbicula" order="Venerida" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="107">Corbicula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Gastropoda" family="Viviparidae" genus="Mekongia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mekongia" order="Architaenioglossa" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="107">Mekongia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
harvests, and were often observed to be discarded along with other large unionids. At some parts of the Tonle Sap Lake, shells of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Simpson" baseAuthorityYear="1900" class="Bivalvia" family="Unionidae" genus="Hyriopsis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hyriopsis bialata" order="Unionida" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="bialata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="107">Hyriopsis bialata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were often covered in mats of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Dunker" baseAuthorityYear="1856" class="Bivalvia" family="Mytilidae" genus="Limnoperna" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Limnoperna fortunei" order="Mytilida" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="fortunei">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="107">Limnoperna fortunei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Rochebrune" baseAuthorityYear="1882" class="Bivalvia" family="Mytilidae" genus="Sinomytilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sinomytilus harmandi" order="Mytilida" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="harmandi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="107">Sinomytilus harmandi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Simpson" baseAuthorityYear="1900" class="Bivalvia" family="Unionidae" genus="Hyriopsis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hyriopsis bialata" order="Unionida" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="bialata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="107">Hyriopsis bialata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is widespread in Indochina, from Thailand to Peninsular Malaysia, and along the middle Mekong basin to the Mekong Delta in southern Vietnam (
<bibRefCitation author="Brandt, RAM" journalOrPublisher="Archiv fuer Molluskenkunde" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" pagination="1 - 423" refId="B8" refString="Brandt, RAM, 1974. The non-marine aquatic Mollusca of Thailand. Archiv fuer Molluskenkunde 105: 1 - 423" title="The non-marine aquatic Mollusca of Thailand." volume="105" year="1974">Brandt 1974</bibRefCitation>
). Recent molecular analyses have revealed cryptic divergence in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Simpson" baseAuthorityYear="1900" class="Bivalvia" family="Unionidae" genus="Hyriopsis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hyriopsis bialata" order="Unionida" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="bialata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="107">Hyriopsis bialata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on specimens from peninsular Malaysia and the Chao Phraya and Mekong basins (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.scitotenv.2016.07.098" author="Zieritz, A" journalOrPublisher="Science of the Total Environment" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" pagination="1069 - 1078" refId="B95" refString="Zieritz, A, Lopes-Lima, M, Bogan, AE, Sousa, R, Walton, S, Rahim, KAA, Wilson, J-J, Ng, P-Y, Froufe, E, McGowan, S, 2016. Factors driving changes in freshwater mussel (Bivalvia, Unionida) diversity and distribution in Peninsular Malaysia. Science of the Total Environment 571: 1069 - 1078, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.scitotenv.2016.07.098" title="Factors driving changes in freshwater mussel (Bivalvia, Unionida) diversity and distribution in Peninsular Malaysia." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.scitotenv.2016.07.098" volume="571" year="2016">Zieritz et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
). Pending systematic revision of this species complex, the name 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Simpson" baseAuthorityYear="1900" class="Bivalvia" family="Unionidae" genus="Hyriopsis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hyriopsis bialata" order="Unionida" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="bialata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="107">Hyriopsis bialata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is herein used for the species in Cambodia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
